  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - BARD</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>HILL GIANTS; ALL YOU CAN EAT</font> - <small>Key Lime Pie, Bertoxxulous</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Using this strategy I leveled from 29 to 36 in VERY
little time.  The best place to do this is in the
Mountains of Rathe.  Start with the Cyclopses and
Giant Skeletons which spawn near the Lake Rathe zone.
As your level increases, you'll start ignoring the
Giant Skels and eventually moving on to Hill Giants.
Basically, find the shallow reds which don't auto-resist
your Charm song, and go to town.<P>

I call the technique "Charm Kiting" and it rocks.  At
35th level I was cleaning the HG's out of the whole
zone and getting <B>bored</B> waiting for respawn.
Solo.  If there are groups of higher-level people
there who also want HG's, it's polite to throw them a bone from time to
time.  =)<P>

Songs to memorize: Charm, Accelerando, Healing, Bellow, and
whatever else.  Have your drum and a string instrument
handy.  Equipment: Load up your Charisma items; it
makes the charms last longer.  Hotkeys: All 3 songs,
plus your instrument hand, and an inventory slot for
the instrument you're not using.  You should always
be in the the "follow me" perspective.  Hit your view key
twice, then back the camera up as far as it will go, and
use ALT-UP ARROW to raise it above the ground.  SHIFT-PGDN
can be used to point it down at you.  Get used to running
around with the camera view way behind and above you.<P>

Start with drum in hand.  You'll almost always be using
it.  Singing Accelerando, run up and smack a Cyclops
with your bare hand, or just pass close enough to
get it frenzied on you.  Let it chase you as if you're
kiting it.  Now you need to find another.  Run past it,
close enough that the clops chasing you will frenzy it
onto you as well.<P>

Now you're in the basic Charm Kiting mode: Two yellow/red
mobs chasing you around.  The basic skill here is to keep 
Selo's always up.  You should be using the arrow
keys to get around, with your left fingers always resting
on your "Charm" and "Selo" hotkeys.<P>

Target one.  If they con different colors, target the
higher level one.  This will be your pet.  Charm it.
If it resists, sing Selo's for a tick and try again.
Eventually, you'll get it charmed.  Once that happens,
it will often start walking off slowly in a random direction.
You need to back up and let the non-pet smack you once.
Once that happens, your pet will immediately frenzy on
it.  This is the <B>only</B> time you should get hurt.
Once the two mobs start fighting, run a safe distance
away and marvel at the glory of it all.. Did I mention
you should always have Selo's up?  Wait there, singing
Selo's, until both mobs stop fighting and start running
at you: your Charm broke.<P>

Now it's wash, rinse, repeat.  Once they're running at
you, stay out of melee range and re-Charm your pet.  Again,
if you get resists, twist in Selo's and then Charm again.
Each time you successfully charm, they'll fight each
other for a while.<P>

Eventually, one or both will be low on hit points.  Now
for the tricky part: You have to make sure your pet
wins the fight.  If your pet is killed while you have him
charmed, his body will disappear and you'll get no
experience!  Bad.  So you have to keep juggling between
the two mobs, trying to decide which one is going to
win.  This is why you charm the higher-level one to
start out: You're playing the odds.  You'll get a feel
for making this decision as you get better -- consider
each mob's level, as well as its current hit points.
Note that you have to get a bit close to a mob for the
server to tell you its current health.  As long as the
winner of the fight is the one you have charmed at the
end, you're golden.<P>

Once your pet has killed off the other mob, he'll
probably start meandering off in a random direction
again.  Wait till the Charm breaks, then loop back around
(with him chasing you) in 1st person perspective and loot the corpse.  When
fighting HG's, you'll probably have to destroy a lot of
copper and even silver to stay unencumbered.  Real
tragedy, huh?<P>

Now that you have only one mob chasing you (your former
pet), you need to find another to kill HIM off.  A word
about former pets: They're really, REALLY mad at you.
As a result, when you charm something to kill them off,
it will take a little time for your new pet to get higher
than you on your old pet's hate list.  Keep circling
around until they're fighting each other.  Did I mention
to keep Selo's up at <B>ALL TIMES</B>?<P>

I can't stress this enough: Keep Selo's up.  You want
to be outside the fray, controlling it, not down in it.  You
should get hit once by each mob, to frenzy your pet
onto it.  That's all.<P>

Advanced topics:<P>

Sometimes your pet will win the fight and be VERY low
on hit points.  At this point, I would often finish it
off with a Bellow Kite.  This does two things.  It lets you
rest for a while, sell, etc.  It also means you get
experience for a non-pet kill which is even better than
the mad exp you've been making so far.<P>

Eventually, you'll get 3 mobs on you.  This doesn't have
to be a catasrophe, it just means that instead of taking
a small breather while two mobs are fighting, you'll have
to keep running around with the third chasing you.<P>

Sometimes you might get spanked and low on health.  If
you're a little bit low, twist in a shot of healing
every time you pause to let the two mobs fight.  If you're
<B>really</B> low, let them chase you around for a
while, and twist Selo's with healing.  You can swap in
your stringed instrument while doing this.<P></td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
